[1]
Date: 18 Jul 2002
From: Luz Alba Fornells <luzalba@bioqmed.ufrj.br>
Source: Reuters, 17 Jul 2002 [edited]
<http://www.reuters.co.uk/news_article.jhtml?type=search&StoryID=1214256>

Hormone scare hurts Europe farmers, feed makers
-------------------------------------------------
HAMBURG: European Union farmers endured tough restrictions on Wednesday, as
officials traced animal feed tainted with a banned hormone, and feed makers
demanded new laws to keep harmful waste out of their products. Some light
appeared at the end of the tunnel for livestock farmers as the Netherlands,
the world's third largest pig exporter, lifted a blanket ban on foreign
sales, subject to stringent safeguards.
And in Belgium, the food chain security body, AFSCA, said all pigs, cattle
and milk tested so far for traces of the hormone in the Netherlands,
Belgium and Luxembourg were clean. "All the tests so far carried out by
AFSCA on animal products are favourable", it said in a statement.
But farmers' representatives warned that farms could face bankruptcy if
such checks for animal feed contaminated with medroxyprogesterone-acetate
(MPA) took too long. "Farmers have to pay to feed their animals but cannot
earn any money by selling them," said Guenther-Martin Beine, spokesman for
north German farmers' association LNL. "If tests take more than a couple of
weeks, some farms will have to close."
Farms in most of the 15 member countries of the EU have been hit and
closures (pending checks for the hormone) have in some cases been in force
since late last week.
Ingredients made by the now-bankrupt Belgian firm Bioland and tainted with
MPA were mixed in feed sent to about half the pig farmers in the
Netherlands, some 7000 farms. MPA is forbidden in the EU and in other
countries as a hormone in livestock feed and scientists say it can cause
infertility in humans. It is a component in pharmaceuticals such as hormone
replacement therapies for women in menopause.
The EU's animal feed industry called for better laws. "It is unacceptable
that animal feed is still regarded as a cheap waste disposal system,"
Fefac, the European Compound Feed Manufacturers Federation, grouping
organisations from 14 EU member states, said in a statement. "Fefac
therefore calls on the European institutions to propose most rapidly a
harmonised regulation for animal feed hygiene aimed at extending compulsory
official approval to all feed material suppliers and to ensure that the
regulation on dangerous waste be correctly implemented," it said.
The Dutch farm ministry said late on Wednesday that farmers could resume
exports, but only following examination of meat from a "test slaughter"
and, in some cases, if they could prove the animals had eaten fresh food
for the past 7 days. Approval for exports had been widely expected after
Dutch authorities and EU veterinarians on Wednesday discussed a protocol
with conditions for exports and slaughter to restart.
The latest in a series of food scares in Europe provoked anger among
farmers whose livelihood was again affected.
"We are sick of being the victims of yet another case of feed
contamination," Beine said. "People are now thinking about joining together
to take legal action against those responsible."
The source of MPA contamination has been traced to waste water from an
Irish pharmaceutical factory owned by U.S. drugmaker Wyeth, Irish officials
have said. The waste was shipped via Irish waste recovery company Cara
Environmental Technology Ltd to Belgian reprocessing plant Bioland, which
mixed it into glucose syrup then sold as raw material to Dutch animal feed
makers. Cara has said there were no grounds for action against it.
Ireland's Environmental Protection Agency on Tuesday alleged "serious
errors" at Wyeth's Irish plant. They said waste water containing the
hormone had been wrongly labelled before being shipped to the Belgian
reprocessing plant.
A spokesman for Wyeth Medica Ireland told Reuters on Wednesday: "Before we
sent them the waste we provided them (Cara and Bioland) with samples,
safety data sheets and all of the constituents of the products and they
confirmed to us they were capable of handling the waste."
Asked if the company expected the waste to end up in glucose for animal
feed he said "certainly not. It was confirmed to us it would be processed
in the correct manner." He declined to comment on reports that European
farmers plan to sue the company for damages and stressed the firm was fully
cooperating with authorities in Ireland and continental Europe.
Officials stress there is no immediate danger to health unless MPA is
consumed over long periods, but any animals testing positive may not be sold.
[Byline: Michael Hogan; additional reporting Abigail Levene, Niamh Keegan,
Otti Thomas and Sybille de La Hamaide]
