[3]
Date: 18 Jul 2002
From: Conor Kretsch <Conor.Kretsch@enviros.com>
Source: The Irish Times, 17 Jul 2002 [edited]
<http://www.ireland.com/newspaper/front/2002/0717/333847724HM1FOOD.html>

Hormone contaminated waste "incorrectly classified"
---------------------------------------------------
The hormone-contaminated waste shipped from Ireland, now at the centre of a
major food scare, was incorrectly classified, the Environment Protection
Agency has said.
In a preliminary report presented to EU animal food experts in Brussels
yesterday, the EPA accused both Wyeth Medica, Newbridge, Co Kildare, and
waste brokers, Cara Environmental Technology Ltd, of mixing hazardous and
non-hazardous waste for export.
As the crisis hit thousands of farms on the Continent, angry Dutch pig
farmers and feed makers threatened to sue the two Irish-based companies.
Half of all pig producers in the Netherlands, 7000 farms, have been put out
of business pending the investigation in all but 4 member-states into the
inclusion of medroxyprogestrone-acetate (MPA) in animal food, which can
affect fertility in humans. The EU Commission for Consumer Affairs advised
that the amount of contamination involved is unlikely to be harmful, but
one German state has urged consumers not to eat meat.
The EPA report, which has been seen by The Irish Times, said non-hazardous
sugar waste from Wyeth was correctly classified and notified to Irish and
international authorities in 1997-99.
"However, in November 1999, following an audit by personnel from the Wyeth
and Cara companies of a treatment company, Bioland in Belgium, the
non-active, non-hazardous waste sugar stream was rerouted to Bioland,
classified as green waste (incorrectly), not requiring notification under
the Trans-Frontier Shipment Regulations requirements and shipped for recovery.
"In July 2000, Cara Environmental sent a trial sample of waste sugar
solution containing MPA to Bioland. The agency did not find documentary
evidence of acceptance of this waste by Bioland, although Cara
Environmental reported a verbal acceptance.
"It appears that from this time on, the 2 waste streams, hazardous and
non-hazardous, were sent as combined shipments and dispatched to Bioland by
Cara Environmental under the green-list classification."
The report added that no notification was made by Wyeth of this change in
procedure or request for permission to send the sugar solution containing
the MPA to Bioland for recovery. This breached the terms of the integrated
pollution control licence granted to Wyeth by the EPA in 1996. It concluded
that the decision to classify the sugar solution containing MPA as "green
waste" was incorrect; and its reclassification led to the waste being
exported without notification to the competent authorities in Ireland or in
Belgium.
Newbridge-based Wyeth said last night it understood the EPA was considering
citing the company in relation to not notifying the agency of a change of
waste processor for the treatment of the waste stream in question. It
pledged to co-operate.
The managing director of Cara Environmental, Mr Brendan Keane, said it had
proof that it had sent samples of the waste from Wyeth to Bioland on 28 Jul
2000, and the decision to classify the material as "green" was made on
those results. "Why would we risk our reputation to dispose of 200 tonnes
of waste like this?"
[Byline: Sean MacConnell and Iva Pocock]
--
